[{"id":"VR871145","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a circuit diagram and a graph. The circuit is composed of a vacuum containing two metal plates, a voltmeter, an ammeter, and a variable voltage source. The left side of the circuit has a vacuum containing two metal plates. Light is incident on the top plate, which emits electrons. Moving across the top of the circuit, it splits into two vertical branches. From top to bottom, the first vertical branch has a voltmeter labeled V and an ammeter labeled A. The second vertical branch has a variable voltage source with its positive terminal on top labeled delta V. The two branches join between the voltmeter and the ammeter, and the circuit is completed. The current I is indicated next to the ammeter by an arrow pointing downward. The graph shows a point in the first quadrant of a coordinate plane. The horizontal axis is labeled “delta V,” and the value 0 is indicated. The vertical axis is labeled “I,” and the values 0 and I sub 0 are indicated, with I sub 0 approximately half way up. A point is on the vertical axis at the value I sub 0.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR871145.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Two metal plates inside a vacuum are connected to a variable source of potential difference, as shown in the figure. One of the plates is illuminated by monochromatic light that causes electrons <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"open parenthesis, e, close parenthesis\"><math alttext=\"open parenthesis, e, close parenthesis\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mo>(</mo><mtext> e</mtext><mo>)</mo></math></span></span> to be emitted, creating an electric current <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I\"><math alttext=\"I\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>I</mi></math></span></span>. When the potential difference <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"delta V\"><math alttext=\"delta V\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mi>V</mi></math></span></span> between the plates is zero, the current is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub 0\"><math alttext=\"I sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span></span>, as indicated in the graph. What happens to <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I\"><math alttext=\"I\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>I</mi></math></span></span> as <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"delta V\"><math alttext=\"delta V\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mi>V</mi></math></span></span> is increased, and what evidence or reasoning supports the claim?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR871145_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I\"><math alttext=\"I\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>I</mi></math></span></span> increases. As <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"delta V\"><math alttext=\"delta V\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mi>V</mi></math></span></span> is increased, more electrons are emitted.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I\"><math alttext=\"I\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>I</mi></math></span></span> increases. As <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"delta V\"><math alttext=\"delta V\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mi>V</mi></math></span></span> is increased, the emitted electrons increase in speed.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I\"><math alttext=\"I\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>I</mi></math></span></span> decreases. As <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"delta V\"><math alttext=\"delta V\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mi>V</mi></math></span></span> is increased, the electric field between the plates reduces the intensity of the light.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I\"><math alttext=\"I\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>I</mi></math></span></span> decreases. As <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"delta V\"><math alttext=\"delta V\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mi>V</mi></math></span></span> is increased, fewer electrons have kinetic energy greater than <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"e delta V\"><math alttext=\"e delta V\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mi>V</mi></math></span></span> and cannot reach the bottom plate.</p>"],"answer":3}]